.TH "ORKTREE\-INIT" "1" "2025" "orktree" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
orktree\-init \- initialize orktree in a directory
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]orktree init\f[R] [\f[B]\[en]source\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Initialize orktree metadata in the given directory (or the current
directory).
Creates a \f[B]<repo>.orktree/\f[R] directory next to the source root containing
\f[B]state.json\f[R] and a \f[B].gitignore\f[R] that prevents the directory from
being tracked by any enclosing git repository.
.PP
If the directory is a git repository, orktrees will be git\-backed (each
orktree gets its own branch and worktree registration).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\[en]source\f[R], \f[B]\-s\f[R] \f[I]path\f[R]
Directory to initialize.
Defaults to the current directory.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]help\f[R], \f[B]\-h\f[R]
Print usage information.
.SH EXAMPLES
Initialize in the current directory:
.IP
.EX
orktree init
.EE
.PP
Initialize a specific directory:
.IP
.EX
orktree init \-\-source /path/to/project
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
\f[B]orktree\f[R](1), \f[B]orktree\-switch\f[R](1)
